                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d161">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860D.00/1148: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Finland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McClintock</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Helsinki</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-02-18T13:00:00+02:00"
                            >February 18, 1943—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 18—12:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>298. Source mentioned in my 297 today<note n="92" xml:id="d161fn92">The source
                        cited in this telegram was Albin Johnson, International News Service
                        correspondent in Finland.</note> said that during conversation with Prime
                    Minister Rangell he was closely questioned as to American peace aims and what we
                    proposed to do after the war was won. Rangell stressed this [<hi rend="italic"
                        >his</hi>] interest in whether United States could exert effective influence
                    on Soviet Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">McClintock</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
